answers.body_markdown:
You can not obtain multiple elements with:

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;data = request.POST.&lt;s&gt;get(&#39;name&#39;, &#39;email&#39;, &#39;comment&#39;)&lt;/s&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

The [**`QueryDict.get(..)`** method [Django-doc]](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/ref/request-response/#django.http.QueryDict.get) takes one or two *explicit* parameters. The first value is the *key*, and the second one is an *optional* default (if you do not provide one, `None` will be used).

You thus can obtain the data with:

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;name = request.POST.&lt;b&gt;get(&#39;name&#39;)&lt;/b&gt;
email = request.POST.&lt;b&gt;get(&#39;email&#39;)&lt;/b&gt;
comment = request.POST.&lt;b&gt;get(&#39;comment&#39;)&lt;/b&gt;
blog = get_object_or_404(Blog_tables, pk=blog_id)
p = commenttable.objects.create(
    blog=blog,
    comment_name=name,
    comment_email=email,
    comment_Text=comment,
    comment_data=timezone.now()
)&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

Instead of getting input data using just post request use [django forms][1] like this

 forms.py


      class CommentForm(forms.ModelForm)
         class Meta:
             model = commenttable
             fields =[&#39;comment_name&#39;,&#39;comment_email&#39;,...]
             #specify your model fields here

Views.py

    def post_comment(request):
        form = CommentForm()
        if request.method == &#39;POST&#39;:
           form = CommentForm(request.POST)
           if form.is_valid():
              form.save()
              return redirect()
         return render(request,&#39;template&#39;,{&#39;form&#39;:form})

Also better use the django standard [url naming conventions][2] in the template instead of writing url patterns


  [1]: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/2.2/topics/forms/
  [2]: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/2.2/intro/tutorial03/#namespacing-url-names

